:::summary
G.K. Chesterton (1874–1936) was the English writer, journalist, and Christian apologist whose dazzling wit, paradoxical brilliance, and deep Catholic faith produced some of the most quotable and persuasive writing in defense of Christianity ever penned — a man of letters who wrote eighty books, several hundred poems, and four thousand essays, and who C.S. Lewis credited with first moving him toward Christian faith.
:::

